    <title type="html"><![CDATA[How to Backup a Website on S3]]></title>
    <link href="http://d-g-h.github.com/blog/2012/05/19/how-to-backup-a-website/"/>
    <updated>2012-05-19T22:43:00-04:00</updated>
    <id>http://d-g-h.github.com/blog/2012/05/19/how-to-backup-a-website</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Some Requirements First:</p>

<ul>
<li><p>Free</p></li>
<li><p>Easy</p></li>
<li><p>Mirrors site</p></li>
<li><p>Interacts nicely with AWS S3 Storage</p></li>
</ul>


<p>After a bit of extensive research I settled on a solution I found over at github called boto-rsync.  The boto part communicates with Amazon and the rsync part&#8230;keeps a track of what has changed and what as not, by dumping files here and there at them it ask what is different and what is not.</p>

<p>Now, there were some challenges, I&#8217;m cheap and I&#8217;m on the lowest plan that my host had, and while it has the support for Python, the language of choice for boto, it does not play nice with other versions of Python that I have on the server. I don&#8217;t want mess with that configuration, even if I could, which I don&#8217;t think I can, but I didn&#8217;t try because it sounds like a bad idea, so the workout around</p>

<p>Install virtualenv -  http://pypi.python.org/pypi/virtualenv</p>

<p>Now, I can whatever I would as long as start this up.
http://pypi.python.org/pypi/boto_rsync</p>

<p>Here is the script that is run by a cron job.</p>

<pre><code>#boots into the virtual env to get boto, boto then mirrors the directories via an rsync of sorts
cd /home/namename/users/.home/my_new_env/bin/
a. activate
boto-rsync -a UUUUUUUUUUUUUUUU -s IIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIII  /home/adfadfadsf/users/.home/domains s3://c.namename.co
</code></pre>
]]></content>
